{
  "text": "Poor-quality antimalarials also have negative financial consequences for healthcare systems, pharmaceutical companies, governments and societies, and their use may potentially jeopardize the investments made in the past decades to control and eliminate malaria [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The lost productivity and increased healthcare costs associated with the use of poor-quality antimalarials generally occur in resource-constrained countries that are already disproportionately bearing the global cost of malaria [36, [CITATION_4] . These countries generally lack the increased financial resources needed to inspect, analyze and police the antimalarial supply chain [CITATION_5] .",
